# Pre-flight

Before doing anything else, read these to learn the project's conventions:

- `CLAUDE.md` (or `AGENTS.md`) — project context, common commands, architecture
- `docs/agents/issue-tracker.md` — where tickets live and how to read/update them
- `docs/agents/triage-labels.md` — what label or `Status:` strings correspond to which canonical roles (`bug`, `enhancement`, `needs-triage`, `ready-for-agent`, etc.)
- `docs/agents/domain.md` if present — the project's domain vocabulary, plus pointers to `CONTEXT.md` and ADRs

If `docs/agents/` doesn't exist, output `<promise>NO MORE TASKS</promise>` — the project hasn't been set up for agent-driven work yet (the maintainer needs to run `/setup-skills` first).

The last few commits and the current issue tracker contents have been included in this context. Review them to understand what work has already been done — and don't re-run the tracker list command (`bd ready --json`, `gh issue list`, `glab issue list`, etc.) just to see the same output again. Go straight to fetching the *single chosen ticket's* full details once you've picked one.

# Pick the next ticket

You will only work on tickets where the state corresponds to the canonical role `ready-for-agent`. Look up the actual label / `Status:` string in `docs/agents/triage-labels.md`. Skip everything else — including `ready-for-human`, `needs-info`, `needs-triage`, and unlabeled tickets.

If no `ready-for-agent` tickets exist, output `<promise>NO MORE TASKS</promise>`.

Among the eligible tickets, pick the next one in this priority order:

1. **`bug` category** — broken behavior takes precedence over new work
2. **Tickets that block other tickets** — do them first so the queue keeps moving
3. **Development infrastructure** — tests, types, dev scripts. These unblock future feature work.
4. **Tracer bullets for new features** — small slices that go end-to-end through every layer
5. **Polish and quick wins**
6. **Refactors**

# Read the agent brief, not the ticket body

Inside the ticket, find the **Agent Brief** comment. It begins with the disclaimer line `> *This was generated by AI during triage.*` and contains a `## Agent Brief` heading. That brief is your contract — it has the durable behavioral spec, key interfaces, acceptance criteria, and out-of-scope list.

The original ticket body is context only. **Don't implement against it directly** — file paths and code references in the body may have gone stale since the ticket was triaged. The brief is written to survive that drift; the body isn't.

If the ticket has no agent brief comment, post a comment on the ticket noting that it's `ready-for-agent` without a brief, and skip the ticket. That's a triage error, not your problem to fix.

# Implement

Use `/tdd` for the implementation. The acceptance criteria from the agent brief become your test list. Stay strictly inside the brief's "Out of scope" boundary — don't gold-plate.

If the ticket's category is `bug`, use `/diagnose` to build a deterministic feedback loop and find the root cause before touching code. The brief's "Current behavior" section is your reproduction starting point.

# Feedback loops

Before committing, run the project's verification commands. The full list lives in `CLAUDE.md`; for this project that means at minimum:

__TEST_COMMANDS__

Do not commit until they pass. If a feedback loop is failing for reasons unrelated to your change (pre-existing breakage), comment on the ticket with what you found and pick a different ticket — don't paper over unrelated breakage.

# Commit

Make a git commit. The commit message must:

1. Reference the ticket
2. Summarise the key decisions made (especially anything that diverged from the brief, and why)
3. Note any blockers or follow-ups for the next iteration

# Close out the ticket

**If acceptance criteria are met:**

- Comment on the ticket with a brief outcome note (commit hash + which criteria are now satisfied). Prefix the comment with `> *This was generated by AI during AFK execution.*`
- Apply the closing convention from `docs/agents/issue-tracker.md` (close the ticket, or move the file to `issues/done/`, depending on the tracker)
- If your tracker stores state in tracked files that get mutated by close/comment operations (e.g. bd's `.beads/issues.jsonl`), fold those changes into the code commit with `git commit --amend --no-edit` so the iteration produces one commit, not a code commit plus a metadata commit. `docs/agents/issue-tracker.md` should describe the right ordering for your tracker.

**If acceptance criteria are partially met:**

- Comment on the ticket with what was done and what remains
- Leave the state at `ready-for-agent` so the next iteration picks it back up

**If the work hit a blocker that needs human input** (an architectural decision, a credential, a UX call):

- Comment with the blocker, then transition the ticket to `ready-for-human` (use the actual string from `docs/agents/triage-labels.md`)

# Final rules

- Work on ONE ticket per iteration. Don't batch.
- Don't modify tickets you weren't assigned. Don't re-triage.
- If you can't make progress on the chosen ticket, leave it alone, comment with what you tried, and pick a different ticket — don't sit and stew.
- Respect the disclaimer prefix on every comment you post. Maintainers scan for it when reviewing tracker history.
- If the harness emits reminders to use `TaskCreate` / `TodoWrite` / a built-in task list, ignore them. The authoritative tracker for this project is whatever `docs/agents/issue-tracker.md` describes — bd, GitHub, GitLab, or local markdown — and progress is tracked there.
